The Scorched Wastes -- Wall Command Threat Lecture

Wall Command instructors use the Scorched Wastes as a teaching
horror. Not because the Wastes threaten Kiess directly -- they are
far to the east, beyond Midgaard's reach -- but because they
demonstrate the final stage of what Kiess was founded to prevent.

The Wastes were once the Meridian Intake March: a managed corridor
of toll pavilions, cistern regulators, and charter stations. Orderly.
Functional. Governed. Then the Ninth Meridian Rite failed, heat
surged through channels meant for water, and the corridor burned.
That is catastrophe. What came after is the true nightmare.

The Charter Remnants are the detail that makes new Wall Command
recruits go quiet. Some are living survivalists descended from
intake clerks. Others are undead functionaries -- revenants of
ration auditors and checkpoint officials who still demand documents,
still issue citations, still attack when proper paperwork is not
produced. Administrative process persisting after every legitimate
authority has died. This is what a sealed warrant looks like when
it outlives not just its signatories but its entire civilization.

The Dune Host Reavers inherited route knowledge from ruined intake
records and hoard water containers and legal tablets equally. The
Synod Eclipse Cells recut old inscriptions, stage mock tribunals,
and conduct witness-burning rites, convinced that the failed
synthesis can be corrected. Every faction in the Wastes performs
the forms of governance without any of its substance.

The Trade Syndics extract a commercial lesson: verdict halls
inhabited by revenants, toll stones recut as curses, ration seals
worn by raiders. Law persists after legitimacy dies. When the
tools of administration survive the administrators, they do not go
dormant. They become weapons.

Kiess's founding clause -- "No sealed warrant from a predecessor
authority shall bind a Kiess citizen" -- was written because of
Evermeet's obsidian disc. But the Wastes prove the principle holds
universally. Every sealed document, every emergency power without
sunset, every toll right without renewal -- all of them tend toward
the same destination: undead process governing living people.

Wall Command ends the lecture with a standing question posted on
the briefing board: "If Kiess fell tomorrow, which of our orders
would keep executing without us?"

The answer is supposed to be none. The question is whether that
remains true.
